1 Sec. A-2. 5 MRSA §285-A, sub-§3, as corrected by RR 2023, c. 1, §1 and affected
2 by §50, is amended to read:
3 3. Voting. All votes of the commission must be one vote cast by labor and one vote
4 cast by management. The votes must be cast by the labor cochair, who must be chosen by
5 the labor members, and the vote must represent the majority opinion of the labor members
6 of the commission, and by the management cochair, who is the State Human Resources
7 Officer or the officer's designee designated by the Commissioner of Administrative and
8 Financial Services from among the management members appointed by the Commissioner
9 of Administrative and Financial Services.
10 PART B
11 Sec. B-1. 5 MRSA §285, sub-§1-A, ¶D, as amended by PL 2021, c. 312, §1, is
12 further amended to read:
13 D. If terminating employment but not retiring at that time, have 25 years of creditable
14 service under chapter 423, subchapter 4 and remain a member of the Maine Public
15 Employees Retirement System, make a one-time election to continue coverage from
16 the date of termination until retirement and pay the cost of the coverage plus the cost
17 incurred by the Office of Employee Health and, Wellness and Workers' Compensation
18 in administering coverage under the plan. If a terminated employee who elects
19 coverage under this paragraph fails to pay the cost of coverage and any administrative
20 costs in the amount and manner determined by the office, the coverage may be
21 cancelled in accordance with the requirements of Title 24 and Title 24‑A. Regardless
22 of election of coverage or cancellation of coverage under this paragraph, an employee
23 terminating employment as provided in this paragraph may elect coverage upon
24 retirement under paragraph E; or
25 Sec. B-2. 5 MRSA §285-A, sub-§1, as amended by PL 2021, c. 312, §2 and PL
26 2023, c. 412, §3, is further amended to read:
27 1. Establishment. The State Employee Health Commission is established to serve as
28 trustee of the group health plan in this subchapter and to provide counsel to the Executive
29 Director of Employee Health and, Wellness and Workers' Compensation and the State
30 Human Resources Officer on health and dental insurance issues, the state living resources
31 program and other issues concerning employee health and, wellness and workers'
32 compensation.
33 Sec. B-3. 5 MRSA §286, as amended by PL 2021, c. 312, §§4 and 5 and PL 2023,
34 c. 412, §3, is further amended to read:
35 §286. Administration
36 The Commissioner of Administrative and Financial Services has responsibility for the
37 state employee health insurance program through the Office of Employee Health and,
38 Wellness and Workers' Compensation that is established as part of the organization of the
39 Bureau of Human Resources. The office is headed by the Executive Director of Employee
40 Health and, Wellness and Workers' Compensation. The executive director has
41 responsibility for the daily operation of this program and for the development and
42 maintenance of programs that promote the health and safety of the state employees.
43 Program services must be administered through offices, systems, consultants and staff
44 necessary to provide cost-effective, accessible and responsive services to eligible
Page 2 - 132LR0158(01)

415 employees and retirees. Administration of the program must be consistent with rules
426 adopted by the State Employee Health Commission. The executive director and the staff
437 of the state employee health insurance program are appointed in accordance with the Civil
448 Service Law.
5 Appeals by eligible employees or retirees shall must be to hearing officers designated
6 by the commission.
7 The cost of administration of the state employee health insurance program shall must
8 be funded from an administrative allowance to be negotiated by the commission with the
9 health benefit carrier or carriers. Indirect costs may not be allocated to the program.
10 The commissioner shall establish the Accident, Sickness and Health Insurance Internal
11 Service Fund through the State Controller in which health insurance and dental insurance
12 premiums collected from state departments and agencies and other plan participants,
13 premium dividends, return of premiums resulting from risk reduction programs and any
14 other receipts must be deposited to be used for the purposes of the state employee health
15 insurance program. The fund is a continuing fund and may not lapse. Interest earned from
16 investment of the fund shall must be credited to the fund.
17 An annual report shall must be prepared for the Governor concerning the number of
18 participants, premiums charged, utilization of benefits and operating costs. The report shall
19 must also include recommendations regarding future operation of the program.
20 A reserve fund, administered by the Executive Director of Employee Health and,
21 Wellness and Workers' Compensation and the State Human Resources Officer with
22 approval of the Commissioner of Administrative and Financial Services, is created to
23 protect the program from unexpected losses and self-insured losses and related expenses
24 incurred in the provision of health and dental benefits for the eligible participants. The
25 fund is a continuing fund and may not lapse. The Treasurer of State shall invest the fund.
26 All proceeds of these investments accrue to the fund.
27 The reserve fund is capitalized by money from premium payments and by legislative
28 appropriation, payments from state departments and agencies and by such other means as
29 the Legislature may approve. All money in the fund is deemed to be the commingled assets
30 of all the covered employees and must be used only for the purposes of this section.
31 Sec. B-4. 5 MRSA §286-M, sub-§2, ¶C, as amended by PL 2021, c. 312, §6, is
32 further amended to read:
33 C. "Division" means the Department of Administrative and Financial Services, Office
34 of Employee Health and, Wellness and Workers' Compensation.
